I wrote a pixel hit test function , it works well utils today. !_!
1. Sprite A { scaleX:2.5,scaleY:2.5}  in scene; 
2. Sprite B {scaleX:0.5,scaleY:0.5}  is included in Sprite A,(B is A's child node). 
3. Render Sprite B to cc.RenderTexure R.
4. Add R to scene, R 's size is the same as  the origin size of Sprite B.

I don't know if it's right logic. I thought  R's size should be the same as the display size of Sprite B.
If Sprite B's size is {width:30,height:30},  
R's size should be 30X0.5X2.5  , but I got 30X0.5.

If this is a correctly result, can somebody tell me how to render Sprite B, make it looks like the same as render from scene?

Here is my code:

``` javascript
var hitTextInPixel=function(glX,glY,target){


        //这里没有使用node.x node.y的方式是因为在绘本里覆盖了.y 得到的y坐标不是GL坐标
        var bounds=target.getBoundingBoxToWorld();

        var originPos=target.getPosition();

        var pos=target.parent.convertToWorldSpace(originPos);
        target.setPosition(pos);

        target.getDisplaySize()


        var winSize=cc.winSize;
        var pixelSize=cc.director.getWinSizeInPixels();
        var renderTexture=new cc.RenderTexture(bounds.width,bounds.height);
        renderTexture.setKeepMatrix(true);

        renderTexture.setVirtualViewport(cc.p(bounds.x,bounds.y),cc.rect(0,0,winSize.width,winSize.height),cc.rect(0,0,pixelSize.width,pixelSize.height));
        renderTexture.beginWithClear(0,0,0,0);

        target.visit();

        renderTexture.end();
        if(cc.JsbHelper){
            cc.JsbHelper.directorRender();
        }else if(cc.director.render){
            cc.director.render();
        }else {
            return true;
        }


        target.setPosition(originPos);







        var w=1;
        var h=1;

        var bytes=new Uint8Array(w*h*4);

        if( renderTexture.readPixels){
            renderTexture.readPixels(glX-bounds.x,glY-bounds.y,w,h,gl.RGBA,gl.UNSIGNED_BYTE,bytes);

            return bytes[3]>0;
        }else{
            return true;
        }



    };
```

Currently, audio pause/resume logic on iOS will be controlled automatically.
Both `SimpleAudioEngine` & `New AudioEngine` on iOS achieve in that way, but other platforms are not implemented. So developers have to invoke `AudioEngine::pauseAll/resumeAll` in the Applegate.cpp, some code like:

``` c++
// This function will be called when the app is inactive. Note, when receiving a phone call it is invoked.
void AppDelegate::applicationDidEnterBackground() {
    Director::getInstance()->stopAnimation();

    // if you use SimpleAudioEngine, it must be paused
    SimpleAudioEngine::getInstance()->pauseBackgroundMusic();
    SimpleAudioEngine::getInstance()->pauseAllEffects();
    // if using new audio engine
    AudioEngine::pauseAll();
}

// this function will be called when the app is active again
void AppDelegate::applicationWillEnterForeground() {
    Director::getInstance()->startAnimation();

    // if you use SimpleAudioEngine, it must resume here
    SimpleAudioEngine::getInstance()->resumeBackgroundMusic();
    SimpleAudioEngine::getInstance()->resumeAllEffects();
   // if using new audio engine
   AudioEngine::resumeAll();
}
```

Developers are confused, they complain that why should we invoke these method for Android while their games run perfectly on iOS.

Any thoughts about this? Should we implement the same automatic `pause/resume` strategy for all platforms?
